qas.question: What is the best-known medieval Chinese name for Tibet?
When did the name for Tibet, Tubo, first appear in Chinese characters?
Who reconstructed Middle Chinese spoken from the 7th century to the 10th century?
What is the best known Chinese name for Tubo?
What book describes the 680-690 emissaries from Namri Songsten?
Who else in addition to Emperor Yang Songsten does the Old Book of Tang describe?
What did Baxter H. William reconstruct?

context: The best-known medieval Chinese name for <b3_0>Tibet<b3_0/> is <a0_0>Tubo<a0_0/> (Chinese: 吐蕃 also written as 土蕃 or 土番; pinyin: Tǔbō or Tǔfān). This name first appears in Chinese characters as 土番 in the <a1_0>7th century<a1_0/> (Li Tai) and as 吐蕃 in the 10th-century (<b4_0>Old Book of Tang<b4_0/> describing 608–609 emissaries from <b5_0>Tibetan King Namri Songtsen<b5_0/> to Emperor Yang of Sui). In <b6_0>the Middle Chinese spoken<b6_0/> during that period, as reconstructed by <a2_0>William H. Baxter<a2_0/>, 土番 was pronounced thux-phjon and 吐蕃 was pronounced thux-pjon (with the x representing tone).
